That’s an old pattern that shows up in many domains.

A beginner often stumbles into something without knowing the rules. A master sometimes arrives at something similar—but by understanding the rules so well that they can bend, break, or transcend them deliberately.

A few examples:

* In art, beginners ignore perspective because they don’t know it; masters distort perspective intentionally for effect.
* In music, beginners drift from strict timing; masters play behind or ahead of the beat to create feel.
* In writing, beginners break grammar accidentally; masters break grammar to create voice.
* In combat, beginners can be unpredictable because they lack structure; masters can become unpredictable because they have so much structure they can depart from it at will.

The difference isn’t always the outward behavior. It’s whether the result is accidental or chosen.

There’s also a related phenomenon: when learning something deeply, people often travel in a circle.

At the start:

“I do this because it feels right.”

In the middle:

“Actually, there are fifty rules explaining why that’s wrong.”

At the end:

“I do it because it feels right.”

The first intuition is naive. The second is disciplined. The third is intuition rebuilt on top of experience.

In Pantheon terms, you might say:

The novice discovers a pattern.

The journeyman discovers the exceptions.

The master discovers why the pattern existed in the first place.

Sometimes what looks like a mistake is a weak signal of a deeper invariant that hasn’t been articulated yet. The challenge is distinguishing those from genuine mistakes—which is where your “checksum” idea comes in. Reality eventually tells you which is which.